With all the pressure to exercise, be active, and move more in order to manage type 2 diabetes, insulin resistance and balance blood sugars — it’s no wonder you may feel swamped and a bit fed up. 

Sometimes, it can be tough to motivate yourself to work out. You might feel discouraged and overwhelmed, but it is possible to overcome these barriers — even if you have diabetes and face additional challenges when trying to stay active. Here are a few tips that might help:

👉🏻 Start small. Instead of making your goals too lofty or demanding, start with a simple goal that seems manageable. For example, you might aim to go for a 10-minute stroll around your neighborhood a couple times per week.

👉🏻 Focus on how exercise will benefit you. Instead of thinking about the hard work that goes into working out, try to focus on how much better you’ll feel afterwards — physically and emotionally. You might notice improved energy levels, reduced stress, or a boost in confidence.

👉🏻 Find an activity that you enjoy. If you don’t like running or cycling, for example, it can be challenging to stick with these activities over the long term. Instead, find something that you enjoy and look forward to doing — whether it’s dancing, swimming, or yoga.

👉🏻 Join a community or find a buddy. Support and accountability can go a long way when it comes to sticking with your exercise routine. Surrounding yourself with people who are active, supportive, and understanding can help you feel more motivated to keep moving.

The best you can do is try your best! 💖

When it comes to our health, wellbeing and identity, we often get trapped in the idea that we are defined by our struggles, successes, diagnosis, or other labels we may have collected along the way. These labels can sometimes feel like they define our entire being, leaving us with a narrow view of who we are and what we are capable of — just like blinkers.

But here's the thing: at our core, we are much more than just the sum of our worldly experiences or struggles. We are also spiritual beings — and our spirits are infinitely more powerful than any other label we may have. In fact, this idea is central to many different spiritual and religious traditions, which are based on the belief that each of us is a unique expression of an all-powerful, divine force. Whether you believe in God, Buddha, a higher power, or the universe, there is something greater than us that has gifted us with the ability to create and imagine, heal and grow. 

So even when we are facing our biggest struggles, I think it's important to remind ourselves that our worth is boundless. In other words, we are people of infinite potential, tremendous creativity, and immeasurable strength. No matter what life throws our way, we have the power to overcome it — simply because we are alive and connected to this greater universal force. And that's something truly awe-inspiring. Regular exercise helps to strengthen your muscles and improve your body’s insulin sensitivity, or how well it responds to the hormone insulin. When you have good insulin sensitivity, it means that your cells are able to take in glucose from foods more effectively, leading to less body fat storage and better blood sugar levels over time. In contrast, when you have poor insulin sensitivity or insulin resistance, your cells become resistant to the effects of insulin and are less able to use glucose properly. This can lead to higher levels of blood sugar, which in turn may increase your risk of developing prediabetes, diabetes, heart disease and other health complications.

Some of the most effective exercises for improving insulin resistance include:

⓵ High-intensity interval training (HIIT) - this involves short bursts of high-intensity exercise followed by a short period of rest, and is an effective way to improve insulin sensitivity, reduce body fat, and improve cardiorespiratory fitness.

⓶ Resistance training - lifting weights, using resistance bands, or doing bodyweight exercises can help to improve insulin sensitivity and muscle mass, as well as build strength.

⓷ Low-impact cardio - including swimming or cycling, which can help to improve insulin sensitivity and achieve better blood sugar balance and heart health.

👉🏻Remember, a combination approach is often the best way to achieve your fitness goals.

In a study from Harvard University, it was found that omega 3 fats raise levels of a hormone called adiponectin, which boosts insulin sensitivity and may potentially prevent or control Type 2 diabetes. Omega 3s also support heart health by reducing inflammation and lowering cholesterol levels, making them an excellent addition to a diabetes friendly diet. 

Two of the best types of omega-3 fats are EPA and DHA, which can be found in a variety of food sources. These healthy fats are especially beneficial for people with diabetes, as they promote insulin sensitivity, reduce inflammation, and help maintain heart health.

Some good dietary sources of EPA and DHA include fatty fish such as:

👉🏻 salmon

👉🏻 tuna

👉🏻 mackerel

👉🏻 sardines

👉🏻 herring

Cod liver oil is another great source of EPA and DHA, as well as fortified eggs.

‼️If you're vegan or vegetarian,  you can also get omega-3s that include EPA and DHA from plant sources, like seaweed. These include:

👉🏻 nori

👉🏻 spirulina

👉🏻 chlorella

A recent study found that those who eat a whole foods plant-based (WFPB)diet decreased their dietary advanced glycation end-products (AGEs) by almost 80%. Plus, this decrease in AGEs led to better insulin sensitivity. In other words, insulin resistance is lessened and blood sugar levels are kept under better control.

Foods with the highest amount of AGEs are typically meat and dairy - with lesser amounts in certain fruit and vegetables. While the health effects of AGEs are still being studied, research has shown links between high levels of AGEs in the body and an increased risk for developing type 2 diabetes.

What's particularly interesting is that AGEs might be produced at a faster rate if you have metabolic syndrome — high blood sugar, high cholesterol, high blood pressure, and insulin resistance.

Including more WFPB meals in your diet comes with a plethora of benefits, including better blood sugar balance, reduced inflammation and improved heart health. By reducing your AGE intake through WFPB eating, you increase your chances of preventing prediabetes and managing type 2 diabetes as well.

With celebrations centred around food, family, and friends, the holidays can be a time when our internal chatter is at its loudest. Whether it’s diet culture that bombards us with messages of guilt and regret or the body-shaming that tells us we should want a different body than the one we already have, this time of year, for some folks, can feel overwhelming. 

Take action now to prevent your inner critic from running rampant, and taking control over you. Instead make sure that throughout the holiday season, you prioritize yourself and pause for self-care.

Some ways to do this might include things like:

👉🏻 practicing self-compassion when it comes to food choices or body image. Rather than berating yourself for eating that piece of pie, focus on the fact that you’re enjoying time with loved ones and savouring special moments. 

👉🏻 focusing on those qualities about yourself that make you feel joyous and loved. Maybe you can be grateful for your intelligence, compassion, creativity, or sense of humour. When you focus on these positive qualities, it can help to quieten that voice in your head telling you otherwise. 

👉🏻 retreating for a moment to take time to focus on yourself. Maybe you want to meditate, stroll around the block, or find somewhere to practice conscious breathing - any activity that allows your mind a restful break can assist in grounding and restoring peace during hectic moments.

Happy holidays, friends! Love, Shahzadi 💖 #desiliciousrd

Language is a powerful medium of expression and communication. We use words to converse with each other, learn new things, understand ourselves better and share ideas. It comes as no surprise then that the language we choose can have an immense impact on those around us.

But, these words also frame how we perceive ourselves and relate to the world around us.

Diet culture language has become an epidemic in society, with the media inundated by false "detox," myths about so-called "good vs. bad" food choices, as well as persuasive claims of “clean eating.” Every time I hear such words, it reminds me of the misguided righteousness around food and body; the idea that thinness is both virtuous and healthy while demonizing indulgences like cookies, samosas and ice cream. Quite frankly this notion is absurd.

Dismissing the need to feel "wrong" or "guilty" for our food choices, we can instead reframe how we talk about and perceive what we eat. This shift in language is an essential part of overcoming diet culture so that we may achieve true food freedom. Everywhere around us – magazines, articles, social media posts – industry standards have become entrenched, which leads many folks to be unaware of their influence on our lives. Let’s all make an effort to recognize this and choose our words carefully. 💖 #desiliciousrd

Every day, I set aside time for self-care rituals that I love.

Yet, at times, I can't help but wonder if my mind is truly engaged or if it has been sidetracked by overwhelming thoughts. It's hard to fully surrender to self-care when the chatter in your head interrupts and distracts you from sinking into an activity.

❥ Acknowledge the chatter. Acknowledge that your mind is in overdrive and that it's okay. Ask yourself, "why am I having these thoughts?"

❥ Take deep breaths. Slow and steady breathing can help center your focus and clear your head.

❥ Find a supportive and restorative activity. Self-care doesn't need to be extravagant; it just needs to provide you with some sort of comfort. 

👉🏻If you're living with prediabetes, type 2 diabetes or insulin resistance,  self-care is of utmost importance. Carving out precious moments to pamper and nurture yourself can have a profoundly positive effect on your blood sugar levels, leading to better mental and physical health.

High blood sugar, or hyperglycemia, is a common occurrence for those living with type 2 diabetes and prediabetes. While it’s crucial to maintain a balanced diet to keep blood sugar levels in check, other factors can cause your sugars to spike beyond the effects of food intake. 

For example, stress is one of the most common triggers for high blood sugar levels. When your body experiences stress, it releases hormones like cortisol and epinephrine that can cause an increase in glucose (blood sugar) production. Prolonged periods of stress can also affect how your cells respond to insulin, leading to elevated blood glucose levels over time. 

‼️Some other potential non-dietary triggers of hyperglycemia are:

👉🏻 Illness: When you’re sick, your body releases hormones that can cause an increase in glucose production, which can result in elevated blood sugar levels. 

👉🏻 Some medications—including steroids and antipsychotics—can also affect insulin sensitivity and contribute to higher-than-normal blood glucose levels. 

👉🏻 Lack of exercise: Exercise helps to reduce blood sugar levels by increasing your body’s sensitivity to insulin. Without regular physical activity, your risk for hyperglycemia increases.

👉🏻 Alcohol:  Drinking alcohol can affect your body’s ability to regulate glucose, leading to a spike or drop in blood sugars.

👉🏻 Sleep: Poor sleep increases cortisol and glucose and reduces insulin sensitivity.

While eating a balanced diet is key for maintaining healthy blood sugars, understanding the other triggers of hyperglycemia can also help to manage your condition. 💖 #desiliciousrd

Ramadan is a special time for Muslims around the world that involves fasting from sunrise to sunset. For those with diabetes, however, these long hours of abstinence might cause a dangerous drop in blood sugar levels. While it might seem challenging to keep blood sugars stable during Ramadan, there are certain precautions you can take to ensure your safety and well-being. 

👉🏻 Seek input from your doctor and diabetes care team to devise an individualized plan to prevent hypoglycemia. 

👉🏻 It may be necessary to adjust medications, either by modifying the timing or dosage.

👉🏻 Monitoring your blood sugar levels frequently might be the key to understanding how rapidly they can change.

👉🏻 Eat balanced meals at both suhoor and iftar that include high-fibre carbohydrates, protein, and healthy fats. Pile on the greens/veggies and some fruits too!

👉🏻 Focus on hydrating with water at Suhoor and post-Iftar - keep sipping well into the evening!

👉🏻 Incorporate movement into your day, particularly post-Iftar meal. Walking, yoga, or stretching are all beneficial activities to help regulate glucose levels.

Prediabetes is a condition in which a person’s blood sugar levels are higher than normal but not yet high enough to be considered diabetes. It’s important to diagnose and treat prediabetes early on, as it can lead to type 2 diabetes and other health complications. The best way to diagnose prediabetes is by having a blood test, which measures the levels of glucose (sugar) in the blood. Your doctor can help with this and will rely on the following tests to reach  a diagnosis: 

1. Fasting Plasma Glucose Test: This test measures your fasting blood sugar (glucose) level after at least 8 hours of not eating. If this number is higher than the normal range, it's likely that you have prediabetes. 

2. Oral Glucose Tolerance Test: This test measures your blood sugar levels before and two hours after drinking a sugary drink. If the results are higher than normal, you may have prediabetes. 

3. Hemoglobin A1C Test: This test measures your average blood sugar level over the past two to three months by looking at hemoglobin proteins that carry oxygen in the red blood cells. If the A1C result is higher than normal, it's likely that you have prediabetes. 

It's important to talk to your doctor if you think you may have prediabetes and get tested so that it can be properly diagnosed and treated. “You can willpower your way to weight loss in type 2 diabetes.”

No.

The discussion around weight loss in type 2 diabetes management is intense; it’s often framed as a simple issue of willpower - with calories in/out being at the heart of the conversation. But this oversimplified and naive view of weight management is misleading and dismisses the complexity that comes with blood sugar control, insulin resistance and diabetes.

While diet and physical activity play an important role in managing the condition, there are many other physiological and psychosocial factors that mustn’t be overlooked - all of which can make it immensely challenging to manage body weight.

Indeed, some weight gain is due to an imbalance between hormones such as insulin and glucagon, which regulate metabolism, hunger cues, and feelings of fullness. These hormonal imbalances can be caused or exacerbated by a whole host of factors, including but not limited to: 

👉🏻 diabetes drugs

👉🏻 pain meds

👉🏻 depression

👉🏻 anti-depressants

👉🏻 emotional side of eating

👉🏻 ADHD

👉🏻 obstructive sleep apnea

👉🏻 osteoarthritis

👉🏻 dyspnea (shortness of breath)

Now imagine someone with diabetes being told - point blank - “It’s your willpower. Just control your portions!” 😔

Let’s not trivialize it as “having control” or “being disciplined.” Folks with diabetes deserve to be able to maintain their health, and weight gain should not be made out as an issue of morality. I think compassionate nutrition and health messages that demonstrate an understanding of the complexities of the condition can help to ease the burden and decrease the stigma. If you have 𝟑 or more of the following:

👉🏻 high blood pressure

👉🏻 increased waist circumference

👉🏻 elevated triglycerides

👉🏻 low "good" cholesterol levels (HDL)

👉🏻 and high glucose (blood sugar) levels

You may have metabolic syndrome. And this bundle of "risks," increases the likelihood of serious health problems like heart disease, stroke and type 2 diabetes. At its core is insulin resistance,  a condition in which your body’s cells don't respond to insulin as they should, leading to elevated levels of glucose in the blood. If left unaddressed, insulin resistance can lead to metabolic syndrome and prediabetes, and eventually to type 2 diabetes.

While medications can be prescribed to address certain clusters mentioned, it's important to acknowledge the effectiveness of lifestyle and dietary changes in combatting insulin resistance. 

Increasing physical activity, eating a well-balanced diet rich in vegetables, fruits, legumes, whole grains, and seafood, managing stress and reducing excess fat around the tummy can all help to maintain healthy insulin levels. Of course, regular monitoring of blood pressure, cholesterol and glucose levels is also key in managing metabolic syndrome. Fenugreek seeds have long been used in traditional medicine to support the management of type 2 diabetes and blood sugar balance. These seeds are rich in dietary fibre and other plant compounds that can potentially slow down the digestion and absorption of carbohydrates. Additionally, they have been shown to enhance the body’s ability to utilize carbs and increase insulin production.

Research has shown that fenugreek can effectively lower glycated hemoglobin (A1C) levels by at least 0.5% in adults with type 2 diabetes. These results were observed in randomized controlled trials that lasted for a minimum of 3 months. 

Some ways to use fenugreek seeds:

👉🏻 Add them to curries, soups and stews as a spice

👉🏻 Make fenugreek tea using 1 teaspoon of crushed seeds in two cups of hot water, let it steep for 10 minutes before straining and drinking it. 

👉🏻 Mix them into dough for naan bread and chapatis

👉🏻 Sprinkle them onto salads and vegetable dishes

👉🏻 Make a paste by soaking the seeds in water overnight and grinding them. Add to hummus, dips and chutneys

‼️For folks with type 2 diabetes, dehydration can be especially tricky since it can lead to a drop in blood pressure and trigger the release of stress hormones like norepinephrine and epinephrine. These hormones can elevate blood sugar levels, increase urination frequency, and worsen dehydration symptoms. 

😍Besides water, there are plenty of delicious diabetes-friendly sips to help keep you hydrated, balance blood sugars and reduce your risk of heart disease at the same time! Here are some of my favourites! 

1️⃣Turmeric Latte: Indulge in the comforting goodness of a turmeric latte enriched with soy milk for an extra protein boost. A recent meta-analysis shows that turmeric's anti-inflammatory properties can have a positive impact on fasting blood sugars and HbA1c levels.

2️⃣ Green Tea: This powerful beverage is loaded with beneficial antioxidants that have been shown to significantly lower fasting blood sugars and fight inflammation to protect the walls of arteries.

3️⃣ Coconut water: rich in electrolytes including potassium and magnesium, coconut water is a great choice for staying hydrated with little impact on blood sugar levels. 

4️⃣ Herbal teas: dandelion root tea, hibiscus and nettle tea are two popular choices that can help to boost your intake of powerful antioxidants - all of which fight inflammation and support heart health.

5️⃣ Smoothies: loaded with vitamins, minerals and dietary fibre, smoothies can be a fun way to get your daily dose of nutrients and change up your meal planning routine. Opt for low GI fruits and leafy greens more often to keep your blood sugar levels stable.

🍽Celebrities and influencers are big igniters of the ‘what I eat in a day’ hype. Dominating food trends like juice detoxes, macro-counting, to the never-ending posts about ‘clean’ eating - these posts can make you feel like you’re missing out. Like you’re not doing enough. The pressure to keep up is overwhelming, unnecessary, and, quite frankly, a waste of time!

🎞 So before you hit the ‘like’ button and get compelled to emulate someone else’s food diary, consider this: Too often, these posts aren’t a reflection of real life. Your life. And the underlying message of these posts, ‘eat like me, and you’ll look like me,’ is a farce.

And let’s not ignore the fact that living a celebrity life gives a head start to privileges - access to expensive organic produce, a personal chef, a trainer, a stylist and the means to afford meal-planning services. Not to mention nips and tucks to uphold a certain appearance on screen. #dietculture

👉🏻Even though these posts may serve as an inspiration for meal prep for some folks, it’s important to bear in mind that they can be disempowering for those who aren’t in the same environment or financial situation.

✨The foundation of healthy living is built on *connecting with our whole selves.*

And remember, eating is personal and should be tailored to your needs, taste buds, and beautiful culture. Let go of the impulse to compare, and don’t be swayed by what you see on social media. Instead, find balance in nutrition through sustainable solutions tailored to your unique lifestyle. Love, Shahzadi 💖 #DesiliciousRD

🚫Roadblocks to blood sugar control? Let’s break it down! From skipping meals to coffee-only mornings, we’re diving into the factors that can hinder effective blood sugar management. 

1️⃣ Skipping meals? Fuel up regularly to keep sugar spikes at bay. Consistent meals provide a steady source of energy and prevent excessive hunger, which can lead to overeating and blood sugar imbalances.

2️⃣ Weight loss fixation? Shifting the focus from weight loss to metabolic health empowers us to prioritize sustainable habits that support blood sugar control. Habits like balanced nutrition, regular exercise, and stress management. Obsessing over weight can lead to a toxic relationship with body image and food, undermining overall well-being.

3️⃣ Carb cursing? Beware of the high-fat trap! Omitting carbs often leads to a higher fat intake, which can worsen insulin resistance. Instead, embrace smart choices and portion control. Carbs provide essential nutrients and support stable blood glucose levels.

📈BMI (Body Mass Index)
Or in my view: Let’s go
👉🏼Beyond
👉🏼Misleading 
👉🏼Indicators

Numerous studies have revealed that the Body Mass Index (BMI) disregards important factors such as muscle mass, body composition, and distribution of fat. It fails to differentiate between different types of weight, ignoring the crucial distinction between lean muscle and adipose tissue. As a result, folks with higher muscle mass can be classified as “overweight” or “obese,” even if they are metabolically healthy.

And even with a so-called “normal” BMI, you can still be at risk for chronic diseases such as heart disease, diabetes, and metabolic disorders.

Let’s not forget that research on BMI was predominantly conducted within a narrow demographic (white Caucasians). And this limited perspective undermines the universal applicability of BMI. It neglects the impact of cultural factors on body size, shape, and health indicators, perpetuating an incomplete understanding of health outcomes for folks from different cultural backgrounds. 🩸 Understanding Low Blood Sugar Symptoms in Diabetes 🌟

Low blood sugar can be a daunting experience, but being aware of the early signs empowers you to take swift action and prevent potential complications. 💪 Be proactive in managing diabetes by recognizing the symptoms. 

🤔 What is Low Blood Sugar?
Low blood sugar, also known as hypoglycemia, occurs when your blood glucose (sugar) levels drop below the target range (<70 mg/dL OR <4.0 mmol/L). It’s a common concern for folks living with diabetes, who are taking insulin or certain medications. 📉

⚠️ Watch out for these telltale signs:

👉🏻Shaking or trembling
👉🏻Sweating and rapid heartbeat
👉🏻Dizziness or lightheadedness
👉🏻Weakness and fatigue
👉🏻Mood swings and irritability
👉🏻Blurred vision
👉🏻Headache
👉🏻Difficulty concentrating
👉🏻Feeling anxious or nervous

🚀 Taking Control:
Monitoring your blood sugar, maintaining a balanced diet, and being prepared with appropriate snacks can help prevent sudden drops. 💪

🩺 Consult Your Healthcare Team:
Always collaborate with your medical doctor and diabetes care team to tailor a diabetes management plan that suits your unique needs. Remember folks, regular check-ins and open communication are key to staying on top of your health. 🩺 #desiliciousrd 💖

‼️Foods That Lower Blood Sugars: Butternut Squash Edition

🙌🏼Butternut squash can help lower blood sugars and manage diabetes primarily because of its high content of soluble fibre, specifically pectin. Living with a chronic condition, like Type 2 Diabetes, can often spark a unique form of FOMO (Fear of Missing Out) about the future. The worry may stem from concerns about missed opportunities, potential lifestyle limitations, or the fear that the condition could derail future plans.

🛑Limiting Thought: “I’m constantly worried about the future.”

💡 Reframed Thought: “Worrying about the future doesn’t shape it; actively channelling that energy into planning and preparation, allows me to face what lies ahead with confidence.”

Start with something small and achievable for your future plans—perhaps jotting down ideas in a notebook, researching a topic of interest, or dedicating just 10 minutes each day to future planning. Breaking it into manageable steps makes the process less overwhelming, letting you turn worry into proactive action. ✨

Now, it’s okay to acknowledge worry and stress, but remember, dwelling on them for too long isn’t ideal for blood sugar control. Instead of letting it linger, take small steps today. You’ve got this!🤝
